subject: Implement $top and $skip
commitMessage:
Implement $top and $skip

$top and $skip are parameters for controlling the responses of
collections, to limit their size, per the Redfish specification section
7.4.

$skip=integer "Applies to resource collections. Returns a subset of the
members in a resource collection, or an empty set of members if the
$skip value is greater than or equal to the member count. This paging
query parameter defines the number of members in the resource collection
to skip."

$top=<integer> "Applies to resource collections. Defines the number of
members to show in the response.  Minimum value is 0 , though a value of
0 returns an empty set of members."

This commit implements them within the resource query.

Tested:
curl --insecure --user root:0penBmc  https://localhost:18080/redfish/v1/Registries\?\$top\=1

Returns 1 value.  Walking through values of 1-5 (there are 4 registries
currently) returns the appropriate sizes of collection (with 5 returning
4 entries).

curl --insecure --user root:0penBmc https://localhost:18080/redfish/v1/Registries\?\$skip\=0

Returns the collection.  $skip values of 0-5 return descending number of
results.

Signed-off-by: Ed Tanous <edtanous@google.com>
Change-Id: Ied8a8f8338f119173509fb4b7ba2bd4a6c49cae8

Whoops, abandoned both.

The spec said $top and $skip only apply to source collections.

Service should return

"
The HTTP 400 Bad Request status code with the QueryNotSupportedOnResource message from the Base Message Registry for any supported query parameters that apply only to resource collections but are used on singular resources. This includes query parameters such as $filter, $top, $skip, and only.
"

> The spec said $top and $skip only apply to source collections.
> 
> Service should return
> 
> "
> The HTTP 400 Bad Request status code with the QueryNotSupportedOnResource message from the Base Message Registry for any supported query parameters that apply only to resource collections but are used on singular resources. This includes query parameters such as $filter, $top, $skip, and only.
> "

That's good to know;  The implementation doesn't do that for $only either;  We don't really have any good way to know which routes are collections and which aren't until after they're done, and even then, we'd have to rely on something like

@odata.type.ends_with("Collection"),

Which doesn't seem great.  As is, this code relies on the existence of the Members variable to determine if the thing is a collection, which seems like an ok intrinsic;   Maybe we just add a 400 QueryNotSupported on line 469 of query_param.hpp instead of returning 500?

query.isOnly is inited to false and not changed in all the calls I have seen. So this is essentially dead code right now?

suggestion: why not split $skip and $top into 2 inline functions. I know the way it is written right if only 1 condition is true the other is a no-op but the code will read simpler. If both conditions are true, you can trust the compiler to optimize and do obj->find("Members") only once, since its all inline code anyway. Also if  $filter or excerpt are added later, the code will flow better.

> suggestion: why not split $skip and $top into 2 inline functions. I know the way it is written right if only 1 condition is true the other is a no-op but the code will read simpler.

Disagree that the code will be simpler.  There will be more code overall.

> If both conditions are true, you can trust the compiler to optimize and do obj->find("Members") only once,

I don't think the compiler is capable of this optimization like you described.  Even if it were, it's not something I'd like to rely on, or duplicate the code for.


> since its all inline code anyway. Also if  $filter or excerpt are added later, the code will flow better.

Can't say I agree with you there.  $top and $skip are very related transforms, and are basically identical code, only differing in the call to arr->erase.  Keeping them together IMO makes sense.  If we abstracted anything, we could abstract out the arr->erase calls, but that just seems like overkill to abstract one liners.

I'm not sure what you're pointing out.  Query.isOnly is changed on line 210 in this file, so no, this is not dead code that I'm aware of.  Also, the line you pointed out doesn't even make mention of isOnly, so I'm a little confused.  Can you clarify, which code you think is "dead"?
I agree the erase call doesnt need an abstract. I guess it fine for now
Done
